00:04:52.650 --> 00:04:54.362
So how do we do that?

00:04:54.362 --> 00:04:56.650
The important thing is
to always visualize

00:04:56.650 --> 00:04:57.710
the shell or the disk.

00:04:57.710 --> 00:05:04.450
So the shell method we're going
to take slivers like this,

00:05:04.450 --> 00:05:06.220
where the width of
that sliver is dx.

00:05:06.220 --> 00:05:08.650
I could draw it really big.

00:05:08.650 --> 00:05:11.510
So that's our direct
angle, is going to be dx.

00:05:11.510 --> 00:05:13.530
What's the height going
to be of the sliver?

00:05:13.530 --> 00:05:15.590
Well it's going to be
the top function minus

00:05:15.590 --> 00:05:16.360
the bottom function.

00:05:16.360 --> 00:05:21.760
It's going to be y equals
4 minus x squared.

00:05:21.760 --> 00:05:25.650
So this is going to be 4 minus
x squared, the height at

00:05:25.650 --> 00:05:27.510
any point right here.

00:05:27.510 --> 00:05:30.880
And then if I were to do
the shell just like we did

00:05:30.880 --> 00:05:36.300
before-- let me see if I
can draw a decent shell.

00:05:40.650 --> 00:05:43.390
I think I'm getting
